            <title>GE survey uncovers who is most likely to buy an electric vehicle</title>
            <description>&lt;p&gt;
	&lt;a href="http://www.gereports.com/just-what-will-nudge-more-consumers-to-buy-evs/" jquery1291833508320="8"&gt;Behavioral economist&amp;rsquo;s Dan Ariely&amp;rsquo;s view&lt;/a&gt; on what will nudge more consumers to buy electric vehicles dovetails with GE&amp;rsquo;s own quantitative look at buying habits. Over the summer, a third-party research firm working with GE asked just over 1,000 consumers to share their thoughts on EVs. About half of the sample were drivers with gas-powered cars, the other half currently drive a hybrid or EV.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	The survey found that drivers have three key needs when it comes to considering an EV purchase.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	The &amp;ldquo;Environmentally Conscious&amp;rdquo; respondents see EVs as symbolizing their commitment to the planet, sustainability, and fossil fuel independence.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="large_img_wtext" sizcache="3" sizset="1"&gt;
	&lt;a href="http://files.gereports.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/seg1-lg.jpg" jquery1291833508320="9" sizcache="3" sizset="1"&gt;&lt;img alt="" src="http://files.gereports.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/seg1-sm.jpg" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;
		&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;
		&lt;span&gt;Green team:&lt;/span&gt; Click to enlarge.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	The &amp;ldquo;Technology and Car Driven&amp;rdquo; consumers make a different statement. Environmental benefits aside, they see the technology as simply &amp;ldquo;cool&amp;rdquo; &amp;mdash; representing cutting edge innovation that puts them ahead of the pack. In tech circles, they&amp;rsquo;re known as &amp;ldquo;early adopters.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="large_img_wtext" sizcache="3" sizset="2"&gt;
	&lt;a href="http://files.gereports.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/seg2-lg.jpg" jquery1291833508320="10" sizcache="3" sizset="2"&gt;&lt;img alt="" src="http://files.gereports.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/seg2-sm.jpg" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;
		&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;
		&lt;span&gt;Wow factor:&lt;/span&gt; Click to enlarge.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&amp;ldquo;Frugal Travelers&amp;rdquo; rounded out the group, with EVs seen as a way to permanently reduce their travel costs &amp;mdash; with the added benefit of being environmentally friendly.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="large_img_wtext" sizcache="3" sizset="3"&gt;
	&lt;a href="http://files.gereports.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/seg3-lg.jpg" jquery1291833508320="11" sizcache="3" sizset="3"&gt;&lt;img alt="" src="http://files.gereports.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/seg-3sm.jpg" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;
		&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;
		&lt;span&gt;Wallets matter:&lt;/span&gt; Click to enlarge.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	As for those that are ready to buy an EV, a recent Deloitte study found the top three considerations when purchasing an EV are vehicle price, reliability and cost to charge.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	Although charging costs can vary based on the electrical grid infrastructure, GE estimates a full charge for a 24 kWh battery using its &lt;a href="http://www.gereports.com/ge-unveils-residential-wattstation-ev-charger/" jquery1291833508320="12"&gt;new WattStation charger&lt;/a&gt; will cost approximately $3.50 &amp;ndash; $4.00, based on average electricity rates.And smart grid time-of-use pricing programs will allow customers to charge their vehicle at an even more efficient rate.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/noria/reliableplant/tags/green_manufacturing/~4/bAbHpoNKjZ0" height="1" width="1" alt=""/&gt;</description>
            <a10:updated>2010-12-08T12:41:02-06:00</a10:updated>
            <a10:content type="text/html" src="http://reliableplant.com/Read/27820/GE-most-like-buy-EV" />
        <feedburner:origLink>http://reliableplant.com/Read/27820/GE-most-like-buy-EV</feedburner:origLink></item>
